<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.latimes.com/news/opinion/la-oe-kennedy29jan29,0,4119647.story?coll=la%2Dheadlines%2Doped%2Dmanual">Our Nuclear Talk Gravely Imperils Us.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
A dangerous world just grew more dangerous. Reports that the administration is contemplating the preemptive use of nuclear weapons in Iraq should set off alarm bells that this could not only be the wrong war at the wrong time, but it could quickly spin out of control.<br>
<br>
Initiating the use of nuclear weapons would make a conflict with Iraq potentially catastrophic.<br>
<br>
President Bush had an opportunity Tuesday night to explain why he believes such a radical departure from long-standing policy is justified or necessary. At the very minimum, a change of this magnitude should be brought to Congress for debate before the U.S. goes to war with Iraq.<br>
<br>
The reports of a preemptive nuclear strike are consistent with the extreme views outlined a year ago in President Bush's Nuclear Posture Review and with the administration's disdain for long-standing norms of international behavior.<br>
<br>
According to these reports, Secretary of Defense Donald Rumsfeld has directed the U.S. Strategic Command to develop plans for employing nuclear weapons in a wide range of new missions, including possible use in Iraq to destroy underground bunkers.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
No prizes for guessing which way that reporter votes. War is war. There are no rules. Death is death however it is delivered. The nuclear option is always open and must be decided upon case by case. If war does happen and Nukes are deemed necessary to minimise casualties and ensure a quick victory then I would support the decision. They worked last time. Atleast this time around they are talking about smaller tactical weapons designed for a specific purpose which isn't obliterating major cities.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 212<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/29/03 2:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Pre-emptive Nuclear Strikes. Good or bad.</span><hr size=1> I would not support premptive nuclear fist strikes on Iraq, the situation does not warent it, nor are they needed. If it was clear that some country was preparing for an imminat first strike against us (DPRK, CIS, France, whoever) then the situation probably would require a rapid takedown of their long range capibility, including the use of nukes. Using nuclear weapons without a similar scale provoking act (ie Iraq gasses masses of American troops), would send a dangerous message to the world and do more longterm harm then good. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 147<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/29/03 4:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pre-emptive Nuclear Strikes. Good or bad.</span><hr size=1> The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>LA Times</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is almost the very center of brain-dead pop-culture radicalism in this country. The &quot;alternate&quot; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>LA Weekly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, with ads for strip clubs and cosmetic surgeons interspersed with recycled 80s radical screeds, is the undisputed center. The Times article completely distorts the policy, turning a highly speculative contingency into a solid plan of action. It also follows the standard line that that this contingency is something new and ominous. In fact, it is not. The US has <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>always</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> stated its willingness to use nuclear weapons under certain circumstances. This article is simply an exercise in scaremongering, based on selective presentation and a seamless transition from fact to speculation;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>ie</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> an attempt to score points and advance the writer's career in the bizarre world of pop-culture elitism. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 773<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/29/03 8:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pre-emptive Nuclear Strikes. Good or bad.</span><hr size=1> Damn AC, it never fails to amaze me how brutally accurate your observations are concerning the rampant ills and idiocy overtaking our society.  In general though I believe nukes should always be a weapon of absolute last resort regardless of the yield of the warhead.  We don't want to take the chance that someone will interpret our use of a small tactical nuke as &quot;permission&quot; to launch their own multi-megaton nukes at someone.  We'd look like hypocrites for telling other countries to restrain their use of nukes if we actually deploy them during wars.  The political problems wouldn't be worth it.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3086<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/29/03 8:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pre-emptive Nuclear Strikes. Good or bad.</span><hr size=1> &quot;the situation does not warent it&quot;<br>
<br>
Who can best decide that? The President with advice from the Pentagon and CIA or us?<br>
<br>
A small tactical nuke far from any sizable town or crop growing area which destroyed a deeply buried vital central communications centre could shorten the war by months. Saving American's and civilians including women and children who might otherwise die in a drawn out conflict. Saddam will be using the populace as human shields. If you pluck the militaries eyes out they will be blind. Take away their leaders in a single strike and they will surrender. Nothing to fight for anymore. <br>
Nobody is going to start firing off nuclear arsenals in response to the US making use of a few small tactical bunker busters. They are very low yield devices. Mutually Assured Destruction guarantees TaiWan won't be attacked by China. Russia isn't going to take on the US. It wouldn't change a thing. Lives are more important than the &quot;nukes are evil&quot; hype. Nukes aren't evil. They are a tool rarely used but kept for emergencies. Their limited use seems reasonable if it shortens a major conflict. Perhaps if nukes had been used in the empty mountains of Afghanistan we could have killed Osama Bin Laden. I wonder what he is planning next. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 260<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/29/03 8:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pre-emptive Nuclear Strikes. Good or bad.</span><hr size=1> i doubt it.  daisy cutters were as far as we need...bunker busters, non-nuclear, are sufficient.  special ops raids are preferable to nuclear strike.  do we really want the public to turn against nuclear when it is starting to become somewhat accepted? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3089<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/29/03 9:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pre-emptive Nuclear Strikes. Good or bad.</span><hr size=1> That's a good point but it's not like Hiroshima and Nagasaki. We aren't talking about wiping out major cities. If Saddam Hussein is taken out hiding in some desert bunker then the people would be cheering. The only threat would be fallout and that would disperse over time. If the winds blow it away from inhabited areas there would be no harm done except to the dictatorship. The public can weigh up the right and wrong of it. I wouldn't preclude nukes before the war has even started. They have to be kept as an option and their possible discussed. Public outrage is worth gambling on if it saves lives. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 779<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/29/03 9:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=365.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pre-emptive Nuclear Strikes. Good or bad.</span><hr size=1> I think Zentrander brings up a good point similiar to what Nucleaon said a few weeks go.   We need to show people that not everything that's nuclear is for war and hazardous beyond contemplation.  The Bruce Gagnons of the world would love it if they had all kinds of emotional laden footage of modern day nuke strikes to make their case that nuclear technology can't be used to benefit humanity.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=t